Today marks an anniversary for me, that many don’t know about, but I’m ready to share my story of the dark side of social media. Without this travesty in my life, I am not sure I would be as strong as I am today. 

📍11 years ago today, I recieved the first death threat of over 400 death threats sent to me from a stalker. I had the FBI on my case, private investigators on my case, my own security team, but I was the one who followed my intuition, and investigation skills, put him in a trap, and caught him myself. Arrested under the Feds, with no bond, but I was the one living in hell. 

I was suicidal. I was broken. I felt alone. No one I could relate to, no one felt the pain I was feeling. I was lost. I was in a dark place. So…

If you ever want to look at my social media and just “assume” my life is easy, think again. Let me remind you of a few traumas I’ve had to endure throughout my life, which has helped shape me into who I am the WOMAN today. 

I don’t want pity. I want you to hear me loud & clear that sometimes your setbacks are for your bounce backs & I’ve done that plenty time and time again. 

I’m ready for my TRUTH.

✨After losing my home and all of my belongings in the Woosley Cali fires in 2018, to having my life threatened by a stalker who sent me over 400 death threats in a four month period in 2012, to being abandoned while pregnant in 2013, to giving birth alone in the hospital in 2014, and to raising my son all on my own for over eight years, to being molested when I was around the age of 10, to being deceived, used and abused by people who I thought were my friends, family, trusted business assosicates, I’ve GROWN! But the hardest setback I’ve faced in my life, was losing my mother last year and recovering from a broken heart… 

Life’s taught me this..

I appreciate everything good that comes my way. I smile hard, because I know what it’s like to feel empty inside. I choose to stay positive, despite a world that has tried to turn me into a bitter woman. Stay above it all, and know that Gods toughest battles, are not meant for the weak. -K

Here’s a little fun down memory lane.. This pic was taken in my backyard in the Calabasas Hills a few years ago with @randallphoto. I loved living by a hiking trail that so very few knew about. I’d spend hours in the grass just praying and talking to God. I was always stressed being a single mother, always trying to find balance for it all. My soul needed nature the most in those times, and so that’s what I did. I would meditate and vision my future and bring my son there on as many sunny days as possible basking in Mother Nature. I miss those memories the most, as those were the moments that helped get me by, bonding with nature in all it’s frequencies. The feelings I get being in the presence of nature — is truly my inner calling. Spring is by far my favorite season, planting the seeds of the future, how about you? 💐

Life hasn’t always been full of riches and success for me. I’ve struggled more than you know, being a single mother, overcoming so much, and rebuilding my life over and over it seems — after one travestiy after the next. But the grace of God, has saved me every time. I’ve been through more life’s pain than most would ever assume, and that’s why I have a responsibility as a woman, to share my story to the world, so I too can help others heal, just as much as this journey has been a healing path for me. For a long time, I was in a dark place, didn’t understand why I had to learn all these lessons but I get it now. Looking back I’m thankful for every heartbreak, every struggle, every hater, or disbeliever. It is my calling to help others, and I will do just that with empathy, knowing what it’s like to feel so low in this life. My heart is a extension of Gods work and I hope my non profit brings great change that we all so need in this world. Thank you @dailystar for the interview. @krmediamentor #DailyStar

Two years ago today, my mothers death broke my heart. Losing her was just unbearable, wishing I could have worked harder or made more money to take care of her more. I had just gotten her a house to live in, when I got the call, but it was too little, too late. I blamed her death on myself for a long time, even though she was sick for many years. Until one night a year ago, she came into my dream to remind me that her death was a gift to me, a gift to break me completely, shatter every part of the old me, so I could rebuild and love myself back together whole as new — to fulfill what I came to do, in my purpose, in her honor. And let me tell you, sometimes living your life to the fullest after a loved one’s passing, is the best gift to give to the world as hard as it may be. Even though that void is there, I know my mother wanted me to be happy no matter what. That’s all that she ever wanted for her daughters. Sometimes heartbreak at your core, is the best thing for your soul, as it helped saved me, and woke me up ✨
